{{use Australian English|date=January 2017}} {{use dmy dates|date=January 2017}} {{Infobox document | document_name = 2016 Defence White Paper | image = 2016 Defence White Paper front cover.png | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = Published front cover | orig_lang_code = en | title_orig = | date_created = | date_presented = 24 February 2016<ref name="Press release">{{cite web|title=Prime Minister and Minister for Defence - 2016 Defence White Paper|url=https://www.minister.defence.gov.au/minister/marise-payne/media-releases/prime-minister-and-minister-defence-2016-defence-white-paper|website=Department of Defence Ministers|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> | date_ratified = | date_effective = | date_repeal = | location_of_document = | commissioned = [[Department of Defence (Australia)|Department of Defence]] | writer = | signers = [[Marise Payne|Senator The Hon. Marise Payne]], [[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for Defence]] | media_type = | subject = | purpose = }}
The '''2016 Defence White Paper''' is a [[white paper]] published by the Australian [[Department of Defence (Australia)|Department of Defence]] outlining a strategic plan for the [[Australian Defence Force]] (ADF) over the following decade. The paper describes the need for improvement in the capabilities of the ADF, and includes a commitment to [[Australian dollar|A$]]195 billion in spending on new equipment and resources, as well as plans for restructure and review of the [[Royal Australian Navy]], the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] and the [[Australian Army]].<ref name="ABC news report">{{cite news|last1=Jennett|first1=Greg|title=Defence White Paper: Australia joins Asia's arms race with spending on weaponry and military forces to reach $195b|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-02-25/defence-white-paper-released-increased-spending/7198632|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=ABC News|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=24 February 2016}}</ref>
==Background== The first Defence White Paper was published in 1976 under the [[Whitlam government]], and new papers were published in 1987, 1994, 2000, 2003, 2009 and 2013.<ref name="Previous White papers">{{Cite web |url=https://www.aspistrategist.org.au/seven-defence-white-papers-by-the-numbers-part-1/ |title=Seven Defence White Papers by the numbers (1) |last=Dobell |first=Graeme |website=The Strategist |publisher=Australian Strategic Policy Institute |access-date=17 January 2017}}</ref>
The Department of Defence issued a [[press release]] on 4 April 2014 stating that it had been instructed to develop a new white paper.<ref name="New White Paper press release">{{cite web|title=New Defence White Paper in 2015|url=http://www.defence.gov.au/defencenews/stories/2014/apr/0404.htm|publisher=Department of Defence|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>
==Recommendations== ===Strategic objectives=== The paper outlines three "Strategic Defence Interests" as fundamentals for further planning:<ref name="White Paper">{{Cite book |url=http://www.defence.gov.au/whitepaper/docs/2016-defence-white-paper.pdf |title=2016 Defence White Paper |date=2016 |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia Department of Defence |isbn=9780994168054 |pages=17–18 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref> #A "secure, resilient Australia"{{snd}}the capability to "deter, deny and defeat" an attack on Australian territory by a foreign military power. A key part of this objective is Australia's [[ANZUS treaty|military alliance with the United States]]. #A "secure nearer region"{{snd}}including security partnerships with the governments and militaries of [[Papua New Guinea]], [[Timor Leste]], and other Pacific island nations. #A "stable Indo-Pacific region and rules based global order"{{snd}}primarily, addressing rising tensions in the Asia-Pacific region, including the increased military power of the [[People's Republic of China]].
===Acquisitions=== The paper sets out a number of specific intended purchases of [[materiel]] and weaponry over the following 20 years, though some had been announced prior to the release of the paper. These include:<ref name="White Paper2">{{Cite book |url=http://www.defence.gov.au/whitepaper/docs/2016-defence-white-paper.pdf |title=2016 Defence White Paper |date=2016 |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia Department of Defence |isbn=9780994168054 |pages=86–108 |access-date=22 January 2017}}</ref> *12 new [[submarine]]s, described as "regionally superior"<ref name="Smh report">{{cite news|last1=Wroe|first1=David|title=Defence white paper: Turnbull government's $150 billion submarine bombshell|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/defence-white-paper-new-submarine-fleet-to-cost-taxpayers-150-billion-20160224-gn32kg.html|accessdate=22 January 2017|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=25 February 2016}}</ref> by Prime Minister [[Malcolm Turnbull]], to replace the [[Collins class submarine]]s *8 [[Boeing P-8 Poseidon]] [[maritime surveillance]] aircraft, and a further 7 aircraft of similar design *12 surface vessels, including 3 [[Hobart-class destroyer]]s and 9 [[frigate]]s of a new design *12 "offshore patrol vessels" to replace the [[Armidale-class patrol boat]]s *7 [[MQ-4C Triton]] surveillance [[unmanned aerial vehicles]] *72 [[F-35A Lightning II]] [[Joint Strike Fighter]]s *A new [[Secondary surveillance radar|ground-based radar]] system *1,100 [[Hawkei]] [[infantry mobility vehicle]]s, and later a replacement for the [[Bushmaster IMV]] *A new [[rocket artillery]] system with a range of up to {{convert|300|km|mi}} *2 additional [[KC-30A]] [[air-to-air refuelling]] aircraft *3 [[CH-47 Chinook]] helicopters *2 new [[replenishment oiler|replenishment vessels]]
